ent incentives—the contributors synthesize an impressive diversity of data, paying special attention to the gross imbalances in educational achievement that still exist between developed and developing countries. They draw out clear implications for governmental policy at a variety of levels, conscious of economic realities such as budget constraints, and point to crucial areas where future research is needed. Offering a wealth of insights into one of the best investments a nation can make, Education Policy in Developing Countries is an essential contribution to this most urgent field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEducation and statezDeveloping countries. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  aeducation, educational, learning, knowledge, professor, academic, scholarly, research, college, university, economy, economics, finance, standard of living, policy, international, global, administration, healthcare, parents, students, classroom, essay collection, anthology, data, statistics, government, political, budget, preschool, wellness, health, incentives.1 aAlderman, Harold, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehrman, Jere R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBleakley, Hoyt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDhaliwal, Iqbal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuflo, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngle, Patrice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernald, Lia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaliani, Sebastian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlennerster, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlewwe, P